05180nam a22008055i 9781978810020DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2019040028  a97819788100207 a10.36019/97819788100202doi  a(DE-B1597)563305  a(OCoLC)1152595428  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aPN2270.A35bM37 2020 7aPER0000002bisacsh04a792.089/960732231 aMason, Clifford, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMacbeth in Harlem :bBlack Theater in America from the Beginning to Raisin in the Sun /cClifford Mason. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b35 b&w images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tINTRODUCTION -- t1. The Beginning -- t2. The Long Night of the Nineteenth Century -- t3. New Beginnings for a New Century: 1890–1920 -- t4. The Twenties: Roaring—a Precursor -- t5. The “Voodoo” Macbeth and the Famished Dawn -- t6. Paul Robeson and the Fifties -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1936 Orson Welles directed a celebrated all-black production of Macbeth that was hailed as a breakthrough for African Americans in the theater. For over a century, black performers had fought for the right to perform on the American stage, going all the way back to an 1820s Shakespearean troupe that performed Richard III, Othello, and Macbeth, without relying on white patronage. "Macbeth" in Harlem tells the story of these actors and their fellow black theatrical artists, from the early nineteenth century to the dawn of the civil rights era. For the first time we see how African American performers fought to carve out a space for authentic black voices onstage, at a time when blockbuster plays like Uncle Tom’s Cabin and The Octoroon trafficked in cheap stereotypes. Though the Harlem Renaissance brought an influx of talented black writers and directors to the forefront of the American stage, they still struggled to gain recognition from an indifferent critical press. Above all, "Macbeth" in Harlem is a testament to black artistry thriving in the face of adversity. It chronicles how even as the endemic racism in American society and its theatrical establishment forced black performers to abase themselves for white audiences’ amusement, African Americans overcame those obstacles to enrich the nation’s theater in countless ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAfrican American theaterxHistoryy20th century. 0aAfrican Americans in the performing arts. 0aAfrican AmericansxRace identity. 0aRace in the theater. 0aTheater and societyzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertArt and Architecture eBook-Package 2020z978311073823008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts 2020z9783110704655oZDB-23-DPK08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Arts, Architecture and Design 2020 Englishz978311070478508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020z978311069033040uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197881002040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978810020423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781978810020.jpg  a978-3-11-069033-0  RUP eBook-Package Frontlist 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a9